,Recommended,315460,22770744,"Posted: 2 May, 2016",all,AjiMundi,"Dig or Die may seems like just another Terraria clones, but underneath the similar mechanics, it is quite a different beast. Its unique mechanics sets it apart from Terraria, and so it is worthy of attention even from Terraria veterans.The two prominent unique mechanics are: liquid and structural physics. Water not only flows down and fills up space, it exerts pressure to surrounding blocks. Building blocks have structural strength, so they can crumble under pressure. No longer can you dive into the ocean, dig a chamber, create a one block thick seal, and 'mine' the water out to start a dry underwater tunnel. Do that in this game, and the sealing blocks will crumble and your tunnel will be flooded, just as it would in real life.Structural integrity will also apply to buildings. You will not be able to create a high one block wide tower with platforms on the side, or that stair structures you used so many times in the other games, because your lower blocks would crumble under the weight. A long one block bridge, highway in the sky? Snap! You get the idea.This game is pretty much under the development, so you will be able to learn these and other features as the game develops. By the time this game came out of Early Access, you will be master at managing water pressure and structural integrity.I will give this game a score of 8/10."
,Recommended,315460,18240255,"Posted: 28 September, 2015",all,Deathcricket,"Alpha games are tough to rate as they are in progress but so far this is a 9/10 for me. I feel as this gets closer to release it will be a 10/10.Pros:- Fun graphics (guy jumps like old school megaman)- Lots of content. (tons of varied enemies, bosses, etc)- Zero bugs. game never crashes, solid physics engine, water behaves rationaly, etc- Fun progression. No grinding, just fun exploring. You can not kill new types of enemies to keep the game from progressing to harder levels if you feel in over your head.-  It's like terraria and Craft the World, with biomes and underwater bases. If you like that type of game this will be most enjoyable for you.- Price/Value. Right now the game is $4.99 which is an incredible value for what you get.- Lovely music/sound effects- Great base defense and tower defense type setup.Cons: (being picky as this game is pretty flawless)- The ships computer in the beginning of the game kinda cheats (scans) and tells you where to find everything, if you want a challenge don't listen to him.- The overcharge cannon has such a high kickback you keep donking your head and sometimes die.- So many enemies come at night digging at you that you frequently create large underground spaces. Would like the AI to better use existing passages and not dig the entire world up trying to get at you. Just bugs me having a base floating there with no rock or passages around it.I dunno maybe it's because I just got done playing Skyshines Bedlam, which was $20 and had 1/16th the content this $5 game has and also was a complete steaming pile of♥♥♥♥♥♥ I'm now biased. But Dig or Die is an absolute delight to play and incredibly fun. I'm completely hooked and haven't had this much fun in ages. I haven't been this excited about a game since Ori and The Blind Forest. You know when it's hard, but not so hard you say ""screw this"" and you just stay up till the wee hours of the morning playing it? That's the type of addicting game this is. Whether it's prefecting you underwater base and getting your safety airlocks in place, or building a rikity bridge across a chasm trying to discover new riches, the game is constantly fun. I can't say enough good things about it.With so many ealry access games out there♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥me off with bugs, lack of content, glitches, crashes, and you name it. This game shines like a uranium nugget in the swamp biom (sorry inside game joke).Just buy it now, thank me later."
