76561198046193516,Recommended,315460,21802678,"Posted: 12 March, 2016",all,Shashlik,"This game will make you start out on easy because of the reviews. You might think all of these reviewers suck at gaming and should jump of a bridge for sucking this hard at a 2D game. Well that's what i thought.You'll start out as a man running around sucking up dirt, trees, grass and other junk. Once you got that outof the way you will start killing everything that moves, assuming every live thing in a game is hostile. You're having a great but confusing time.Next you'll start crafting stuff, a shotgun, a few wooden blocks and probably a turret or two. Then night starts to fall.You don't think much of it so you'll just continue making yourself a little cottage. The night slowly grows darker.It is pitch black, several enemies try to attack you and seem to be breaking through your new house! You fight them off with your shotgun and the sun rises again. It sure was one hell of a night.The next day you start looking for the materials and resources you need to make the next thing you want, maybe armor or a flashlight. You encounter new animal species and annihilate them on the spot.Night falls and you rush back to your half destroyed home, quickly patch up the holes and get ready for another group of enemies. They won't catch you off guard this time.You see the enemies coming, your turrets starts to shoot and off you go fighting for your life once again. You notice the new species you encountered seems to have joined the enemy army, but no fair match for your skill!Sun rises once again and you rush out to collect and explore, ignoring the fact that you nearly died last night because you never had a second to look at your health bar. Time to annihilate new radioactive animals for pleasure and resource to get yourself a brand new shiny gun. Rather quickly sunset kicks in once again.Night has fallen and you're starting to lean back a little bit, assuming you'll see victory again. Many many more enemies come. The easy blue flying things and the dog-like kanines don't appear, but instead red flying beasts drilling through your house in a fraction of a second, feral beasts running at you, your turrets all destroyed almost in an instant and you surrounded by enemies, when suddenly...Everything stops. The foes charging at you casualy roam around the area. Then you realize you're not moving. Words appear on the screen saying: you are dead. You are dead.You ♥♥♥♥ed up easy mode on the third night. You retry from the morning of day three trying to get more turrets, a better gun, healing kits, yet still you fail at night. You can't make it past night three.This game is hard. Peaceful mode makes enemies harmless, easy mode rips your clothes off, bends you over and ravages your rear, tearing you a fist size dilation only to call you out for the ♥♥♥♥♥ you are and leaves you to rot in a ditch.It'll take me some serious effort to learn how to not fail as quickly as i did."
,Recommended,315460,20388217,"Posted: 7 January, 2016",all,Jhereg,"I'll be honest. I was a terraria addict for a long time. Then came Starbound, and I was smitten with that too. There were times I wanted to take the building tool for Starbound and give it to Terraria and other such things.I wasn't sure what I was expecting when I started Dig or Die.  The graphics are very simliar, but the playstyle is very different. The basic concept, dig stuff up, build things, survive the night. That's all there, but Dig or Die adds a few things. One of those things is water. Water pouring down from the heavens and flooding your base because you forgot to plug that hole that radioactive alien firefly punched into the dirt to come eat your face the night before...This game instills paranoia. Water paranoia. There is also that moment of ""oh crap did I kill something on accident with my plasma rife?!"" and the moment when 50 angry friends of his come to stomp you into the dirt when night falls. That's paranoia right there.There that frustration that the game has physics, but it is also a sort of love/hate relationship that makes the game it's own thing. You can't just pile up bricks forever. Eventually, that tower has to have support or it's coming down. You can't build a bridge without supports. You have repair walls that took damage or there is a good chance that the night waves will say hello through the hole in your wall.Overall, this game  had a very satisfying feel to it, despite it being early access. I happen to really enjoy the soundtrack and hope there will be more from said composer. Best of all, the devs are active on their discussion board, and they even had time to answer my noob questions (from the gal that literally has only been playing this game for 19.9 hours according to steam...) as well as l isten to my suggestions from a new players standpoint. That's the kind of thing I like to see, and that makes the modest price-tag on this game worth every  penny."
,Recommended,315460,14999418,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,K!netic,"This is a game that seems to have watched what people didn't like about other sandbox games, and worked extremely hard to avoid those problems. Jumping into the game, it's clear that this game doesn't intend to waste your time. The menus and overall feel are extremely smooth and quick. This seems to permeate the whole game's design; don't waste the player's time, let them do what they want, and look good doing it.To start, most sandbox games take forever to mine a block. This one doesn't. And while the time it takes to mine a dirt or stone block decreases with better tech levels, it never feels  arduous to cut through a mountain or dig a tunnel. Which I think is fantastic in a game that's about digging tunnels. Your character occupies one block of space, and it takes under a second to mine one block.After playing a bit, you get to the ""building"" part, which is even simpler. The game dispenses with the idea of you manually putting down blocks of dirt that you picked up. Instead, you mix concrete and place *that*. It's one of about five basic block types you can place. While that seems limiting, it's actually freeing. I've never enjoyed making dirt palaces with haphazard streaks of cobblestone and sand. It lets you focus on the stuff you actually want to do; dig tunnels, get resources, craft new things, and fight monsters.(spoilers ahead)But the real treat comes when you're told to go westward to pick some flower if you want to craft the next tier. while the world itself is randomly generated, there's a giant chasm in the west, cut straight through the ground. You need to build a bridge over it in order to cross, but it's not as simple as just laying down concrete - if a structure is too unbalanced or too much weight is placed on one block, the whole thing falls apart. You're forced to design a bridge that can cross the chasm. Similarly, there are floating islands that contain a mineral you need for a different tier - and you have to build a tower to reach them. While these are fairly scripted things to do, it felt surprisingly good to be given a well thought-out challenge in a building game, yet still have the feel of random generation and freedom.While this game may not last forever, it gives you a great experience for a few hours, and seems to respect you as a player. It knows you've seen it all before, but it knows you quit playing those other sandbox games for a reason - and it's determined not to have those same problems."
76561198027819327,Recommended,315460,15897382,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,Jayne_Cobb,"Dig or DieWell, I died. But I'll dig again. In fact, I dig the digging in this game.Dig Dug, was the first thing that came to my mind. Good oldAtari 2600 madness.This was an impulse buy. And although it's just closing in to v.0.1,I'm already having way too much fun. I played barely an hour,and I'm gonna be just in time for an appointment, becauseof lingering here, writing these lines and already have thefeeling, I got my money's worth.The fighting is fun. It has a little Mega Man vibe, but withoutthe punishment. The crafting isn't getting tedious, so if youlike your crafting without the micro-management overkillthis might feel just right. But, I'm not too far in, although,art direction, controls, environment, sound score, it allsits right at the moment.40 hours in, I'm still having a jolly good time. The communitythat evolves around Dig or Die is also quiet friendly and helpful.Not to a small part to the developer, who manages to be kindand communicative at all times.I especially like the approach to difficulty. Mastering the gameon normal, you'll find new challenges on brutal. Adapting yourapproach. Enemies will only attack you at night, when youprovoked them in the day. So you can save, and have alook how deep you want to get yourself in trouble.While I thought myself master of the world on normal,I was jumping around like a crazy ferret with a laser gunon brutal. After some tries, then finally, the first survivednight on brutal. A victory, all the sweeter, for having learnedfrom previous mistakes, that never got tedious.The game doesn't hate you. When you learned another trick,you'll think to yourself, yeah sure, howcouldn't I have seenthat before? Cool beans! And now to the next adventure!There's also an often updated devblog, that's alwaysworth a visit, at:http://gaddygames.tumblr.com/March 2016 - Dig or Die has hit version 0.2The graphics have gotten a complete overhaul.Physics have been expanded. A.I. has gotten smarter.Increased diversity in monsters, fauna and flora. I thoughtit might have become too complex, but Dig or Die stillhas its unique charme. Even though crafting isn'treally one the most regarded mechanics for me,I find myself returning on this rainy planet.May 2017 - Dig or Die has hit version 0.3betaIt's been a year since I have played Dig or Die.The game has continued to be constantly updatedin the past year. The systems have become moresolid, the user-interface has been optimized andthe physics have grown more complex withoutinducing tediousness to the game formula.Version 0.3 is about to leave beta soon,with multiplayer being introduced."
76561197970362126,Recommended,315460,17506079,"Posted: 12 August, 2015",all,Mr. Fibble,"Dig or die is still in early access and has just had the 0.1 update. Before that you could get off planet in the space of an in game week with ease ending the game. Now there are bosses to fight, more areas to explore with materials and things to craft from them and the promise of more to come. Patches at the moment are very frequent and tend to be not much more than a few kilobytes.The game has an interesting way of pacing the difficulty which is explained by the ai computer in the wreckage beside you at the starting point. This happens in a couple of ways. One is that at night creatures become hostile and will be even more inclined to want to chew your face off than during the day. The other that some people might miss out on is that creatures only become hostile if you start killing them first. So if you run and gun during the first day there's a good chance that come nightfall death will follow.You know those games about building a bridge on a tight budget where you end up making something from girders and knicker elastic? In some ways that is similar to how building works in dig or die. The higher you build the more stress blocks get and once they get too much things will collapse. So with the exceptions of floating islands having a skybase a la terraria isnt possible. Thankfully you can craft goggles that will show stresses when they're on the hotbar that make things a bit easier.There's also rain, more than the average scottish summer, and that brings some changes as well. Digging requires a bit more thought as some tunneling habits will lead to death by drowning. The good news is that the water can be controlled and used for power or just flooding the world to save building up to the islands overhead.Weaponary comes in handy for both killing stuff, obviously, as well as mobility. Rocket jumping isnt a new concept in video games, strangely enough the rocket launcher isnt the best for it in DoD, but a lot of the weapons have a knockback to them which means if you need a boost to cross a gap shooting down will give you the nudge needed. Sililarly if you're swimming in the ocean and start running out of air shooting down can get you to the surface faster.Value wise, one playthrough from start to getting off planet should easily get you below the £1 per hour mark. Currently on around 30p per hour and falling so in the realms of witcher 3's levels of cost per hour.And one last thing that I really like is that, unlike terraria, you aren't forced into looking at a wiki to find out what to do next. All the info you need to play is in the tooltips or mentioned by the crashed ai. It might not say specifically where to go for the black grass but it's easy enough to figure out black dirt is involved."
,Recommended,315460,14832761,"Posted: 10 March, 2015",all,Large,"This is a great game, the buiding physics are well done (but hard to get used to) and a really fun game to play and progress through. I personally think this game would be AMAZING with multiplayer or co-op. If you're lacking a good cheap game this is the perect choice. It kind of feels as if it were a tower defence game but you have to defend yourself with turrets."
,Recommended,315460,18736172,"Posted: 28 October, 2015",all,Asvarduil,"Once upon a time, an interstellar salesman went station-to-station, selling the AwesomeMatic 2000 matter reprocessor!  It slices!  It dices!  It performs molecular restructuring, and YOU can have it for only 2000 Space Dollars!  After this brilliant, and original sales pitch, however, the salesman found out the hard way they tried cold-selling the wrong person.  Captain Benjamin ""Don't F@#$ With The"" Sisko punched them in the throat so hard, they crash-landed on a remote jungle planet.Dig Or Die is a neat little block-building game in the vein of StarBound, Terraria, MineCraft, and all of the clones spawned thereof.  The first thing that's apparent after starting the game, is the influence.  This game appears to draw significant aesthetic influence fromMega Man- notMetroidlike Terraria does, or the Cthulhu Mythos like both Terraria and MineCraft do.  As a result, the game has a very retro feel, in a good way.What WorksAlso, the game is very difficult, but in a (mostly) good way.  The early gamesucks.  You have crappy tools, no facilities, and have to hastily cobble together some form of shelter before the thankfully-super-short night falls, and you get beset by waves and waves of monsters.  I've died a couple of times so far before I've gotten the second-level workbench, but not in a ""BS"" way - usually I die because the game is asking something of me, and I didn't do it.What makes itmoredifficult, but also a deeper game, is you can't build structures that are sustained by videogame logic.  Nonono.  If you want a roof on your structure, you need to build supports.  Walls are helpful.  Also, monsters do damage individual blocks, which means by night the packs of wolves and space-bats can tear down a side of your carefully constructed base.  Even if that doesn't happen, failure to properly reinforce your buildings and placing one block too many causes part of your building to fall down...causing you to need to put it all back in place again.  As a gamer used to video game logic, this is both incredibly refreshing, but also something that I find I've gotten used to not considering as much as I should.Further - point defenses.  Something Terraria and MineCraft just don't have.  You absolutely have to use point defenses to protect your structures...but they do have their limits!  Still the presence and use of point defenses to protect your structures during night brings up on big point that the game does well - unlike most block-buildy games,everythingis useful.  Even the Dirt.Especiallythe Dirt - Dirt is a prime component of Concrete, a reasonably resilient material that has good structural properties.What Doesn't WorkOn the one hand, I don't want to cast my vote too early - and make no mistake, this game is inearlyaccess.  It has a good ways to go before I consider this a completed game.  That being said...critique time.The game's balance is off - the initial difficulty curve is simply too high for my tastes.  While everything above is a strength, it's expressed in the most painful way possible.  Certain monsters like the fish regenerate HP more quickly than you can damage them, leading me to be very hydrophobic in this game.  The monsters for some reason can tear down your wood/concrete walls.  Digging through dirt, I understand.  But wolves, spacebats, and fishes headbutting concrete until it breaks?  That's an innovation only videogame logic could pull off.The visuals need some work - the Mega Man aesthetic is neat, but poorly realized, and lacks cohesion between various elements, particularly the game and the UI.  Speaking of the UI, the UI does not scale well at all - the only setting I can reasonbly play the game on is 1366x768; at 640x480 Windowed the UI is unusably small.  Also on the note of scale, the blocks being as large as the player feels off too.  I usually expect the player to be larger than a single block.  The game would work better if the player were 1x2 blocks, and all enemies were about 50% larger.Speaking of the UI, the in-game UI is very awkward.  There are more item hot-slots than there are top-row keyboard keys, which means you're obliged to use your mouse scrollwheel to be able to select items (of which you get a lot.)  Now, this wouldn't normally be so bad - after all, it's close to how I play Terraria.  Where things go downhill, is that the inventory UI itself is very unlike anything else in the block-buildy genre.  I find myself expecting a grid of items I own - uncategorized - but instead of the inventory UI being helpful as it's no doubt intended, it feels wrong.  This may be personal bias, but I think this game's inventory/hotbar system actually breaks the established genre interface, thus making the experience feel more off than itshould.The TL;DRAt $4.99, in this early phase of development, with the good points and problems all factored in...this game isworth it.I forsee it only getting better as it catapaults to, and past the 1.0 version.  As long as the developer remains engaged, and keeps putting great effort into this game, I think they've made a game that beats a lot of its competion in the Sci-Fi Block Buildy genre -especiallyStarBound and Edge of Space.I will update this review as the game evolves further."
,Recommended,315460,33059638,Posted: 30 June,all,Prettiest Nazi,"IntroMy initial reaction to this game was, oh hey a terraria clone, doesn't look that bad. Can check it out see if it's of any worth and refund if not right? Well wrong, I can't refund it now and I never would in the first place, this game proved me it was of well worth extremely quickly. Especially with the new multiplayer update the game got a whole lot better.The Game SummaryThe game takes place on some random planet after your ship has crashed. In order to get back home you most fight all sorts of powerful monsters, and mine in order to get the items in which you need for escaping and protecting yourself. This game is a lot more ""reality"" based then the game most compared to it, Terraria. In the world you will haft to survive from monsters who will break through anything to get you, while the world is constantly flooding with rainwater, that builds up rather then being like Terraria and just disappearing. However building big to escape this will not always be an option, because there is actual gravity that affects blocks.ConsEveryone wants the cons first,  you watch the video, you get interested, you don't want to read about the pros you can already see in the video. So what are the cons? There's actually not to many other then usually stuff that is bias to the player.It's not really possible to do decorations to make the builds look nicer (paintings, furnichur for the most part, and overall block designs). However even then it does have some legitimacy behind why this would be a lack of things. Reading through the story, the very short and just why you need to leave this planet story, it's apparent that you're not there to make it look pretty but rather to get off as fast as possible.Neither Pros Nor ConsThe block, background, and enemy design, is not the worst, nor is it the best. But before you call me a hypocrite because up there I mentioned block design as a con, I was describing them for decoration along with thing's I'd like added like furniture and such. But blocks alone is meh, not bad nor great, along with the 2 other things on this bullet point.Enemies can break through just about anything, this can be annoying, but for the most part you are probably looking at this game because it provides that challenge unlike games like Terraria. And even then that's why you get turrets that can heal things and others that can shoot.Updates, at least from what I've seen, wipes all game progress. Now you may be thinking nope not buying, but it's actually not bad. This game very rarely updates, I'd say about once a year. Now you may be saying okay well that's a problem in and of itself just adding on. However to it's credit it does do massive updates.ProsAre you afraid that your pc, laptop, microwave, may not be able to run this game? Fear not this game runs very smoothly, especially with how minimum the minimum requirements are shown, it just screams you're gonna get 60 fps without much sacrifice if any.This game overall provides a very nice challenge with very nice physics and AI.The music is very good.This game is a game where you don't haft to be embarrassed to say you did it on easy difficulty.There's multiplayer.The updates are massive and add tons of new content, the latestv0.3 updateadded a whole lot more to the game, and it went from v0.25 to v0.3, which would not be seen as a big change by most just looking at how small the number difference is.Has full command modability.ConclusionIf you like what you see in the trailer, you're gonna like what you play, hands down no regrets,9.2/10."
