,Recommended,315460,23019852,"Posted: 16 May, 2016",all,DoubleCakes,"There's nothing wrong with a game taking heavy inspiration from a popular title if said game does enough to differentiate itself from the title it is taking inspiration from. Dig Or Die differentiates itself from Terraria by taking the Terraria formula and emphasizing tower defense and construction elements while significantly compacting the experience.In Dig Or Die, you play a man who has crashed on an alien planet and must build a rocket ship to escape. You do this by collecting resources and gradually climbing up the tiers of a crafting system until you can build a rocketship and leave the planet. You'll have to survive until then and when nighttime comes that's when the party arrives. Nights in Dig Or Die are short but brutal. The player is swarmed by monsters and the best course of action is to build a base with several turrets because even if you have state-of-the-art firearms it won't be easy taking out the enemies by yourself.Tower defense is a large part of Dig Or Die. The main challenge throughout the game will be surviving the nights as increasingly difficult enemies attack you during nightfall. The game allows you to control how quickly the game's night assault difficulty increases by only adding in a type of enemy into the night defense roster after you've killed it during the daytime in its natural habitat. Turret construction will also come in use when you are fighting bosses because chances are your weapons won't be killing them quick enough.The other big gimmick with Dig Or Die is the construction physics. Anything that's not built in front of a natural background wall will have to abide to the game's complex physics systems. You cannot just simply build a pillar of blocks to the sky, no. The player will have to build eventually because some biomes (and therefore, some crucial resources) are trapped away beyond neverending chasms and the like. It's a very satisfying puzzle, building these constructions and this reviewer enjoyed it a lot even though sometimes it was hard to understand how weight distribution worked.One thing that doesn't get mentioned enough is how Dig Or Die plays with spectacle. Finding new biomes and new enemies is very thrilling and its pretty surprising how deep you can dig down into the earth. Your journey will take you to some very exciting places and there are all sorts of surprises to uncover, at a pacing that sets it ahead of Terraria.In conclusion, those looking for a briefer and quicker Terraria-like experience with heavy defense elements and a construction system that provides interesting puzzles should give Dig Or Die a purchase."
,Recommended,315460,16766562,"Posted: 28 June, 2015",all,BOT freeman,"The only real negative reviews for this game are one of two things, People who dont understand that there are building physics or people who have not got past night 1 and or have not played the game >1/2 hour. Buy the game now if you like physics based games, There is a decent amount of content right now but it is still Early Access. If you cannot make it past night 1 find a sky island, dogs are primarily the thing that kills my base but with the sky island you are safe from said dogs. That will get you past night 1 allowing you to experience the game past your first half hour. My biggest criticism is that the game goes by too fast. Overall 8/10 buy it now!"
76561198048312377,Recommended,315460,31859460,Posted: 20 May,all,TwitchTV_Vantazzy,"I've played Terraria and it's highly adventurous clone: Starbound. Dig or Die a clone? Sure, the same gaming platform/concept. Before you throw bricks at me, I am from that ERA where we call games that uses the same platform/concept CLONES (example: Wolfenstein 3D = Depth Dwellers, Corridor 7, Blake Stone, Operation Body Count) - (example 2: Doom = Heretic, Hexen, Shadow Warrior, Duke Nukem 3D) - (example 3: Command & Conquer = Starcraft, Age of Empires, Rise of Nations)Okay, to my review and verdict of this game.Let me just make a list of things to explain this game easier for seeing the bigger picture:- Structure Integrity (like building a bridge is okay, as long you use support blocks, the stronger the support blocks, the stronger the entire structure will be without collapsing)- When it rains, it's not just rain, it's like an ocean coming down, floods everything! You can use it for your advantage, if you play your cards well through though.- Difficulty Rises when you kill an enemy type the first time (the more different types of monsters you kill, will show up more during the ""bloodmoon"" that happens every night - now it's not called a bloodmoon, but it also doesn't tell me on which planet I am or whatever, but at night it becomes crazy and all monsters are focussed on you)- One Life (sure, if you die, you can start from your last save, but everything which you have collected during that lost gameplay, is lost, because it never happened)- The MAP is procedural generated, with solid hotspots where certain things are always there. Like the vulcano is to the right for example. From left to right, it's not very big, but from top to bottom, it's frickin' HUGE!!!!!- Collect all sorts of ore to craft better equipment, stronger blocks, upgrading, etc..  The deeper you go, the more ore types you will find. Some rarer then the other.- The whole buildup of activities just adds up perfectly in balance, making this game challenging and long lasting.- Try to build a powersystem that can power your base for an unlimited time. (like solar panels only give you power during the day and water turbines only when there is a flow of water, but can be continiously if you use basins and pumps to keep the water flowing)- It's not only building a base and you are done. You need to protect it with turrets. During a bloodmoon, monsters are so angry, so determined, they will destroy blocks in order to get to you. If you made a base on support blocks, I hope for your sake, monsters will not target those support blocks or your base will collapse to the ground (or whatever is down there)So you need to be strategic how to build a base, how to defend it and use it to benefit from it without dying during that bloodmoon. Because if you die during a bloodmoon, the entire day, everything you have built is GONE - never happened... Crucial to survive that night of horror!- Certain items need to be collected, some harder to get, some need some smart thinking...  Like, do you need to build a base right away? Make a base underground, above ground, on support blocks, under water?- No bookcases, chandeliers, vases, flowergardens... No, you are stranded on this planet and you are not staying for long. The goal in this game is simple: Get your wiggly♥♥♥♥♥off this frickin' hostile planet!- Eventually you need to go very very deep under the ground. Where there is LAVA and lava eats through basically everything. There are items down there which you need and even your mining laser cannot get through that thick substance, so you need to use explosives to rip those items out of the walls. The moment you do that, the integrity of the surrounding walls can get comprimised and wakes up the lava, continueing eating through the walls again and making your trip back to the surface a pain in the♥♥♥♥♥♥or even worse: impossible.- The only ""adventure"" are your trips down there, trying to get the ores to get progression and eventually succeed in getting off that planet. The more your progress, the better equipment you get and certain things can be easier. Like teleportation devices. Although they need power to operate, they can speed up travelling to certain points on the map.By saying all this, making me want to play this game again. :DNow this game is still in development, I totally recommend this game!!! The challenge is compelling. But, if you are more of a gamer that wants more exploration, treasure hunting, quests and such, this game might not tickle your senses.And by saying that (hoping the developer reads this bit of my review) - because of the lack of like ancient structures, ancient technology... I would like to have that in this game too. Like that there are very challenging ancient buildings/spacecrafts somewhere, top or bottom, its random, very difficult to enter because they have turrets too, walls are undestructable so you can only enter them where there are open rooms and as treasure special items like a jetpack or a diving suit or a legendary mining laser or a powerful defense drone or a special weapon...And because they are ancient, you need to place cables to the doors, connecting it to a powersystem so you can actually open the doors... That kind of thing... Like a little diversion of the solid gameplay for getting a very special item that is like... not craftable but very handy. <--- Just an idea, think about it..."
