76561198052386399,Recommended,315460,23224043,"Posted: 26 May, 2016",all,Sekai,"This is a game about digging and how it will inevitably lead to death by exploding mosquitoes, fire breathing mosquitoes, plasma shooting mosquitoes, or some other form of mosquito equipped with logistically unlikely projectiles.The game is won by successfully drowning yourself without being hit by mosquitoes.  Other obstacles you will face are uppity regenerating pro-life fish, bending water (that is presumably being bribed by the fish to obstruct your quest), and floating cactuses that will fall out of the sky because they are depressed or their home sports team did not win the championship.Before you can properly drown yourself, you will need to scrounge for materials and develop technology in order to build a basin large enough to hold the necessary water without exploding because gravity, and equip it with automated defenses to keep away both the fish and the mosquitoes, as well as put the water in its place, should it decide to tilt or twist in an unhelpful manner.Finally, you will need to build a rocket ship and program it to launch your carcass into space, because if you can't have a space funeral then what is the point?  Turning on the rocket will summon large quantities of protesting fish, mosquitoes, and angry water that your defenses will have to deal with on their own because at this point you will already be dead, so this requires some planning and engineering skills, and for me was one of the more enjoyable aspects of the game.The rocket blueprint is questionable and probably was stolen from someone's 8th grade science project and sold on Craigslist, as the primary material needed to make it is the still-beating heart of an immortal space rock that floats in the atmosphere and probably was important to maintaining the planet's ecosystem, as killing it causes it to fall out of the sky, followed by a lot of rain, frogs, earthquakes, locusts, volcanic eruptions, plague, and a sudden disparity in the ratio of pro-life fish to their more aggressive eastern European cereal mascot shark counterparts, but what's important is that you get your awesome space funeral.  Good luck, soldier."
