76561198032249196,Recommended,315460,22806971,"Posted: 5 May, 2016",all,Lancar,"A good shorter game (by crafting game standards) of about 12-15 hours.Dig or Die is fairly reminiscent of Terraria, having several similarities, but differentiates itself on it's more modern focus.Whereas Terraria would be all about the bosses, RNG weapon/item drops from monsters and fantasy, and Starbound is about the exploration of strange new worlds and upgrading your spaceship, Dig or Die is a shorter more personal story about survival and escape from a hostile planet.You are accompanied by your ship's AI that, like the Guide in Terraria, gives you advice and hints on what to do next. You're free to do whatever you want, however, as the enemy progression in the game is cleverly tied into the exploration.Every night you're assaulted by rabid creatures that want to rid the planet of your presence, but the only ones that attack you are species you've already killed a member of.The bases you build are basically just forts with one singular purpose: to keep you alive at night, There're a myriad of traps and turrets available to choose from, and each is useful in its own way. As you advance up the tech tree, more toys become available to help protect you against the new & nastier enemies you've angered to get there.Finally, I'll talk a bit about the water physics.The water is this game is the best implementation of it I've seen in any crafting game ever. While it's a bit overexaggerated in it's flow and abundance, it otherwise behaves just as you expect water should.The game simulates pressure, flow and absorbtion to a very impressive degree. Massive rainfalls ensure you always have to contend with it, or have your bases and mines flooded. Dirt will absorb water into it, which is released underneath it or when broken. Mining underwater is a hazard due to the inability of crafting air pockets, as the water pressure pushes the surface upwards.You can also harness the water for use with hydroelectric dams and pumps, and managing the flow of water to your advantage is a constant concern.Physics is also applied to forced acting on the blocks you place.While underground this is a non-issue, as the blocks are always supported by the background layer, but above ground (and other places where there's no background layer) you have to consider thw weight and resistance of the blocks you place, or the whole construction will come crashing down.I kinda wish it'd simulate the different kinds of material stresses better, as even concrete cannot stand vertical towers for very high before it just bursts, but at least it provides an engineering challenge.So:In summary, Dig or Die is a fun little crafting game focusing on survival and tower defense elements in a (partially) physics driven hostile world.I had fun with it, and for the pricetag you could certainly do a lot worse.It's a charming little game, with some cool engineering puzzles to solve and fun combat.Oh, and the battle music kicks♥♥♥♥♥;)"
