,Recommended,315460,23265338,"Posted: 28 May, 2016",all,arc1618,"Dig or Die is an exellent mash-up of tower defense and 2D mine-crafting. It reminds me very favorably of Terraria 1.0 but with its own unique twist. You start off marooned on an unfriendly planet after crashing your spaceship with nothing but an all-purpose mining tool and a crafting station. To survive you'll need to quickly gather all the materials to build a base capable of holding off the hordes of enemies that will swarm you at night. Gameplay is simple but functional; you mine and harvest materials and enemies to upgrade your Miniaturizer and Auto-Crafter so you can build bigger and better guns to kill bigger enemies with. Eventually you'll gain access to the materials needed to build a rocket and escape the planet.Now, after reading several reviews that warned of the game's difficulty, I decided to start my first game on normal, which turned out to be fairly easy. The fact that new, stronger enemies only attack at night once you've killed one of their type coupled with my tendency to overprepare meant that I never died at night and rarely died at all unless I overextended myself. My second playthrough was on brutal, which was an entirely different ballgame. The combination of increased enemy health and decreased player health meant that my first night was only beaten through luck and many reloads. It was still fairly easy once I farmed enough turrets, but there were some massive difficulty spikes on nights when I had killed a particularly tough enemy (like red or explosive fireflies) to upgrade my Miniaturizer but couldn't gather enough of the newly available resources to build stronger turrets.Perhaps the biggest difference between Dig or Die and other block simulators is the stress mechanic. Every block has two values; strength and weight. The strength of a block determines how much weight it can support. If the block's strength is exceeded, it breaks, usually causing a chain reaction that brings down the entire structure. This means players must focus a lot more on engineering than normal. Building up with a 1-block wide tower will only get you killed as the base collapses, while building a dam is much harder than simply placing dirt in the way. However, blocks placed on a background wall never break, so this mechanic is much less influential than it could be.Dig or Die's power mechanic is also somewhat unique. Unlike redstone or Terrarian wiring, every circuit in Dig or Die requires an active power source to function. For most of the game, this means solar panels or hydroelectric power plants; no portable or storable power is available until the very end of the game. However, there are a full complement of logic gates, timers, and sensors available to use, so creating an energy-efficient teleporter or automatic airlock is not that difficult.Once you beat the game, you gain access to the Epilogue, with an infinite Auto-Crafter and Jetpack. This is not creative mode; you do not have invulnerability and enemies will still try to kill you, but with infinite resources it is much easier to take on ambitious projects, like draining the underground ocean, plugging the Volcano or flooding the entire surface.Overall Dig or Die is extremely well-polished for an Early Access game and is well worth the asking price. I highly recommend it to anyone who enjoys Minecraft, Terraria, or games like them."
