76561198074264915,Recommended,315460,14834503,"Posted: 11 March, 2015",all,][sentrop|[,"For my full review and other delicious content seeGlitchDeveloped and published by Gaddy Games, a small indie studio that has dabbled in both the gaming and advergame markets, Dig or Die is a 2D, sandbox, strategy/adventure game currently in early access. You are a galactic salesperson, selling automated fabrication tools. On a recent trip your ship crash lands on a strange planet, full of hostile creatures. You must put your fabrication tools to good use, and gather the local resources to build the structures and weapons needed to explore this new world and survive the nights.The game kicks off with the protagonist outside their crashed ship, and leaves the player too start exploring and gathering resources. The crashed ship's AI offers some timely advice about some of the native creatures and some ideas on how to survive. Using your Miniaturizor you can mine the basic items of the world, and by killing different enemies collect valuable resources to build defences, and upgrade weapons and your autobuilder.I like this minimal instruction, as it is great fun getting in over your head in the early game. As you learn more about the world and find different resources, you will build stronger walls and the more powerful weapons and turrets needed to survive the onslaught of creatures each night. The night onslaughts are great fun, and have a tower defence feel.As you progress the game starts to get a good rhythm , of exploring for new resources, then collecting all you can, before choosing a defensive location and digging in for the night. After surviving the night, I found it best to pack up my modest camp and move on in search of more resources. The resource gathering is well paced, and the requirement to upgrade your autobuilder repeatedly, to get to the best building materials, weapons and Miniaturizor is a great motivator to take risks when exploring.Overall, I was quickly drawn in and addicted to the rhythm and exploration in Dig or Die. I found the pacing to be spot on, with each day cycle giving you just enough time to increase your overall resource pool, before fighting out the night. The upgrade system with the autobuilder, dangles the carrot perfectly and had me searching every inch of this world for weird and wonderful resources. I can't wait to see what other craftable items become available throughout this games development, and recommend this game to anyone who enjoys sandbox creation and exploration."
