,Recommended,315460,24088830,"Posted: 4 July, 2016",all,Jinzo,"Dig or Die... Oh boy.On the outside, given a casual glance, it just looks like yet another TerrariaCraft, which is understandable, as the core gameplay does revolve around blocks and monsters. That's pretty much where he similarities end, though.While in most other sandbox games the enemy is likely some kind of monster, or group of bandits, or other people, the enemy in DoD is a little bit different. While there are scary monsters that would love nothing more than to turn you into a fine paste, they are easily taken care of by using armor, a gun, and a turret or ten. No, the real enemy of the game is physics. You need to be sure that you build your base with a strong foundation to keep it from crumbling, and you want it strong, but not too heavy, or it could collapse. some players in the early game may seek refuge in a hovel dug out of the side of a hill, where they will notice that by building on the back wall. By building on the back wall, you don't have to worry about your base crumbling due to its own weight. What you DO have to worry about (and this is amplified quite a bit if you decide to use hydroelectric generators) is having your base flood. Because the game actually has a real system of water physics, it can easily flow into any airpockets you try to make. This makes using actual doors instead of just an opening in the wall really important. Because of the incredible water physics, you need to be very cautious when it comes to blocking tunnels, especially if you have an underground base.At times, this almost seems like a puzzle game, with the goal being trying to figure out how to build a stable structure that gets the job done.I doubt I need to tell you that I really like this game, and I'm not even much of a builder. The game is 100% worth every last penny."
