,Recommended,315460,15316439,"Posted: 11 April, 2015",all,Lord Shaxx,"To be honest, I first saw this via gameplay posted by Chimneyswift. It looked fun, and the fact that it was so inexpensive also helped me along. For me, the fact that it is currently in early-access means I get to actually have a game from its release, and watch it grow and evolve. The game itself is one I enjoy. A lot. It is reminescent of Terraria, but it has a stronger grasp on physics. I discovered that to build a bridge across a certain chasm, I needed to have a huge support for one half, then I had to use the shotgun's recoil to jump to a small ledge on the other side, and build another oversized concrete arch. I managed to connect the two, and it didn't fall!The guns have recoil in the game, with the shotgun having the most as far as I have experienced. You can aim in the opposite direction of where you are going and pull the trigger, preferably while jumping, and you'll propel yourself across the terrain with ease. It reminds me of rocket jumping in TF2.Now, onto the enemies: they start out nice and easy, just your basic horn hounds and whatever the bee thingies are in the beginning. The bees are ranged, but the power crystals they drop are essential. You are able to craft some turrets early on, and you WILL need them when night comes. Luckily, night is rather short, but very intense. I have survived maybe seven or eight nights, and have lost an unfortunate amount of my turrets. This is due to the black variant of the bees having a long burst of stinger-plasma-bolt-thingies, each dealing 6 damage with-out armor. They melt terrain, and your defenses along with it.It all creates a unique and difficult challenge, which I quite enjoy. The music is... Incredible, to say the least, and the gameplay is addicting. I don't really know what I could recommend to be added, because I just have no idea WHAT to add. I'm a player, not a programmer. (No, not THAT kind.) So, all in all, this game has my attention, and it will keep my attention. I am eager to see how it all unfolds."
