,Recommended,315460,15239061,"Posted: 6 April, 2015",all,Some Guy,"First off, I would like to congratulate the developer for being one of few that I did not regret buying an early access game from.Dig or Die is one of the few gems in early access ATM, and it brings something new to the table when it comes to sidescrollers. The goal of the game isn't as simple as many would like to think. First, there's fighting monsters, then digging, then searching for rare plants atop a giant mountain - this game has it all. There are many things about this game that stand out to me as a gamer. One being that the blocks have weight. Though the blocks do not fall over if you hit them, they can and will break if you build them as if you were building in Minecraft. For building large structures, there are blocks you can place to hold up ceilings and other roofs. Another thing is water. You'd think that water wouldn't be a problem, but on the planet you're on, it is a huge one. Forget just digging a hole and covering the entrence to survive, because water will drip from the dirt blocks all around you until you decide to put some actual walls up. And did I mention that enemies can dig, too? Yeah, this game is challenging, but that's where crafting comes in. There are 3 tiers of crafting that are actually well-balanced for being a fairly new game. I'm not going to spoil them for you, but they are categorized by different auto-crafters, each one requires the previous to be made. Each tier also has a new turret(s), allowing you to lock down areas of the map with force. They are also your lifeline at night. The most prevalent mechanic in the game is the day and night cycle. Imagine Dying Light, but 10 times worse (in a challenging way). Enemies are absolutely vicious at night, turning the game from adventuring to tower-defense in a split second. You'll need to think quickly in order to survive away from your base at night, or else its GG for you. Thankfully it auto-saves after every night.Overall, I give this game an 8/10, even though I usually set my limit on early-access/beta/alpha games at 7/10. With the price set at only $3, you have nothing to lose when trying this game."
